 and Alfred Hershey between 1940 and 1960—and how this novel research program became the foundation of the field of molecular biology. These three young, charismatic, and iconoclastic scientists were convinced of the importance of bacterial viruses (bacteriophages) to the study of the gene and of heredity in general. Based on substantial archival research, numerous participant interviews collected over the past thirty years, and an intimate knowledge of the relevant scientific literature in the field, William C. Summers has written a fascinating new history of the American Phage Group. Rather than a linear narrative of progress by past heroes, this book emphasizes the diversity and historical contingencies in the group’s development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aCommunication in politicsxTechnological innovations. 0aDigital mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aDisinformationxTechnological innovations. 0aMolecular biologyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPropagandaxTechnological innovations. 0aSocial mediaxPolitical aspects. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Molecular Biology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074978640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300269086?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300269086423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300269086/original  a978-3-11-074978-6  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY